d": false, "mention": "1H,1H,10H,10H-perfluorodecane-1,10-diol", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9989792704582214, "span": {"begin": 3285, "end": 3324}}, {"id": ["mesh:C546883"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "FC-10 diol", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9996157288551331, "span": {"begin": 3326, "end": 3336}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:2099"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "hepatic esr1", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.993553102016449, "span": {"begin": 3364, "end": 3376}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:246319"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "vtg", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9899477362632751, "span": {"begin": 3381, "end": 3384}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "fathead minnows", "obj": "species", "prob": 0.8503968715667725, "span": {"begin": 3453, "end": 3468}}, {"id": ["mesh:D008731"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "methoxychlor", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9993852376937866, "span": {"begin": 3480, "end": 3492}}, {"id": ["mesh:D004967"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "estrogen", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9997183680534363, "span": {"begin": 3501, "end": 3509}}, {"id": ["mesh:D020888"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "VTG", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9997358918190002, "span": {"begin": 3550, "end": 3553}}, {"id": ["mesh:D008777"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "methyltestosterone", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.985740602016449, "span": {"begin": 3606, "end": 3624}}, {"id": ["mesh:D000728"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "androgen", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.999607503414154, "span": {"begin": 3638, "end": 3646}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:246319"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "VTG", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.980546772480011, "span": {"begin": 3682, "end": 3685}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "fathead minnows", "obj": "species", "prob": 0.8886271715164185, "span": {"begin": 3710, "end": 3725}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "fathead minnows", "obj": "species", "prob": 0.8013318181037903, "span": {"begin": 3761, "end": 3776}}, {"id": ["mesh:D020888"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "VTG", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9964878559112549, "span": {"begin": 3818, "end": 3821}}, {"id": ["mesh:D008777"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "methyltestosterone", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9921239018440247, "span": {"begin": 3958, "end": 3976}}, {"id": ["mesh:C038254"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "methylestradiol", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9995129108428955, "span": {"begin": 3980, "end": 3995}}], "text": "Original text - unknown contributor  A wide range of studies using adult fish show that induction of plasma vitellogenin (VTG) occurs within 21 days in vivo aquatic exposure to estrogen receptor agonists (eg 17beta-estradiol and 4-tert pentylphenol) as shown during the successful validation of the OECD Test Guideline 229 and related protocols. A smaller number of experiment studies with fish have shown that within the OECD Test Guideline 2010, larval fish can also show induction of whole body VTG levels within 21 days aquatic exposure to estrogen receptor agonists.   &nbsp;  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  Added by C. Baettig June 24, 2024  There are numerous publications supporting this relationship including multiple review articles (e.g., Matozzo et al., 2008; Palmer &amp; Selcer, 1996; Verderame &amp; Scudiero, 2017). A few specific examples are listed below.    Estradiol and diarylpropionitrile (DPN), an ER&beta; selective agonist, induced a dose-dependent increase in VTG synthesis in rainbow trout hepatocytes (Lea&ntilde;os-Casta&ntilde;eda &amp; Van Der Kraak, 2007).  DPN has also been shown to increase ER&alpha; and vtg expression and synthesis post-injection in Mozambique tilapia in vivo (Davis et al., 2010).   A study focusing on benzophenone derivatives found that BP1 (2,4-dihydroxybenzophenone), BP2 (2,2&prime;,4,4&prime;-tetrahydroxybenzophenone), and THB (2,4,4&prime;-trihydroxybenzophenone) were human ER&alpha; (hER&alpha;) and hER&beta; and rainbow trout ER&alpha; (rtER&alpha;) and rtER&beta; agonists. To investigate ER activation profiles of the derivatives in vitro tests, i.e., competitive binding, reporter gene based assays, vitellogenin (Vtg) induction in isolated rainbow trout hepatocytes, and proliferation based assays were completed. hER&beta; was more strongly activated, which is an inverse finding to natural ligand 17&beta;-estradiol (E2) where hER&alpha; is more strongly activated. BPs were more active in rtER&alpha; than in hER&alpha; assays. Significant VTG induction was detected in hER&alpha;, hER&beta;, rtER&alpha;, and rtER&beta; cultures (Molina-Molina et al., 2008).  Tollefsen et al. (2003) looked at multiple endogenous (e.g., estrone (E1), estradiol (E2), and estriol (E3)) and exogenous estrogens (e.g., ethynyloestradiol (EE2), diethylstilbestrol (DES), genistein, zearalenone, bisphenol A) and found they induced dose-dependent VTG synthesis in Atlantic salmon hepatocytes.  Shen et al. (2021) used in silico methods to screen 1056 pesticides for potential agonistic activity. They found 72 pesticides to be potential ER agonists, 14 of which have been previously reported as ER agonists. To test whether these pesticides were ER agonists, 10 were selected from the list, three that were previously reported as ER agonists and seven previously unreported as ER agonists. They found all 10 pesticides exhibited ER&alpha; agonistic activity in human or zebrafish cells and of the 10, seven also induced vtg1 and vtg2 mRNA in zebrafish.   Xu et al (2020) also showed increase in plasma VTG following exposure to aryloxy-phenoxypropionate (APP) herbicides, after measuring the binding patterns of quizalofop-P-ethyl (QPE), clodinafop-propargyl (CP) and haloxyfop-P (HP) with ER&alpha;.   In male fathead minnows exposed to E2 and 1H,1H,10H,10H-perfluorodecane-1,10-diol (FC-10 diol) for 21 days expression of hepatic esr1 and vtg were both significantly increased (Ankley et al. in prep).  In male fathead minnows exposed to methoxychlor, a weak estrogen agonist, there was a clear induction of VTG (Ankley et al. 2001). In the same study exposure to methyltestosterone, a synthetic androgen, caused a significant induction of VTG in both male and female fathead minnows. This level of induction in female fathead minnows resulted in a dose-dependent increase in VTG, to concentrations approximately 10-fold higher than those observed in control fish. These funding were likely due to the conversion of methyltestosterone to methylestradiol (Hornung et al., 2004).", "timestamp": "Mon Jun 08 14:35:28 +0000 2026"}